    What does violet shampoo do to your hair?
    An AI Overview is not available for this searchCan't generate an AI overview right now. Try again later.
    AI Overview
    Purple shampoo helps neutralize brassy, yellow tones in blonde, silver, or lightened hair, restoring a cool, bright, and refreshed blonde look. It achieves this by using color theory, specifically by depositing violet pigments that counteract the unwanted yellow hues, according to L'Oreal Paris. 
    Here's a more detailed explanation:
    • Color Theory:
      Purple is the complementary color to yellow on the color wheel, meaning it can cancel out or neutralize yellow tones. 
    • Neutralizing Brassiness:
      Purple shampoo deposits violet pigments onto the hair shaft, which effectively counteracts the yellow or brassy tones that can develop in blonde, silver, or lightened hair over time. 
    • Maintaining Cool Tones:
      By neutralizing unwanted warmth, purple shampoo helps maintain the cool, bright, and vibrant appearance of blonde hair. 
    • Not for Dyeing:
      Purple shampoo is not a dye; it's a toning product that deposits pigments to correct the tone of the hair, according to L'Oreal Paris. 
    • Use Between Salon Visits:
      Purple shampoo is a great tool for maintaining the cool tones of blonde hair between salon appointments. 
    • Potential Side Effects:
      While generally safe, overuse of purple shampoo can lead to a slight purple tint or make the hair appear dull or darker, says Redken. It can also dry out the hair if used too frequently.

      Is violet shampoo better than purple shampoo?
      Purple shampoo versus Violet shampoo

      Though close neighbors on the color wheel, violet has a bit more blue, while purple has a dash more red. You can guess what that means when you are seeking to “cool down” your brassy yellow tones. The extra blue calms yellow and orange tones more directly.

      Is purple shampoo or blue shampoo better for GREY hair?
      An AI Overview is not available for this searchCan't generate an AI overview right now. Try again later.
      AI Overview
      For grey hair, purple shampoo is generally recommended over blue shampoo. Purple shampoo neutralizes yellow or brassy tones that can develop in grey hair, helping to maintain its bright, silvery appearance. Blue shampoo is more effective for neutralizing orange or red tones, which are less common in grey hair. 
      Here's a more detailed explanation:
      • Purple Shampoo:
        Grey hair, like blonde hair, can be prone to developing yellow or brassy tones due to environmental factors and the natural aging process. Purple shampoo contains violet pigments that counteract these yellow tones, keeping grey hair looking clean and bright. 
      • Blue Shampoo:
        Blue shampoo is designed to neutralize orange and red tones, which are more common in darker hair colors, such as brunettes, that have been lightened. 
      • When to use purple shampoo:
        If you notice your grey hair developing yellow or brassy tones, it's a good time to incorporate purple shampoo into your routine. You can use it once or twice a week, or as needed, depending on how quickly the yellowing occurs. 
      • Considerations:
        Purple shampoo can be drying, so it's a good idea to follow up with a moisturizing conditioner. Some people also prefer using a purple conditioner instead of a shampoo, according to paige ditullio.
